6LU7 | SARS-CoV-2 Main Protease ($M^{\text{pro}}$)Biological Role: The main protease ($M^{\text{pro}}$ or $3\text{CL}^{\text{pro}}$) is a non-structural protein essential for the replication of the SARS-CoV-2 virus. Once the virus invades a host cell, it translates its genetic code into long polyproteins. $M^{\text{pro}}$ acts like molecular scissors, cleaving these massive polyproteins at specific sites to release individual functional viral units needed to assemble new viruses.Structural Mechanics: It operates as a homodimer (two identical protein chains working together). Each monomer contains a catalytic dyad consisting of a cysteine ($\text{Cys}^{145}$) and a histidine ($\text{His}^{41}$) residue. In the 6LU7 structure, a designed peptide-like inhibitor named N3 is chemically bound directly to the active site cysteine, locking the scissors open and completely shutting down the enzyme's replication capability.
